  Month                    = oct,
  Pages                    = {82-84},
  Volume                   = {478},

  Abstract                 = {Mergers of neutron-star/neutron-star binaries are strong
 sources of gravitational waves. They can also launch
 subrelativistic and mildly relativistic outflows and are
 often assumed to be the sources of short gamma-ray bursts.
 An electromagnetic signature that persisted for weeks to
 months after the event would strengthen any future claim of
 a detection of gravitational waves. Here we present results
 of calculations showing that the interaction of mildly
 relativistic outflows with the surrounding medium produces
 radio flares with peak emission at 1.4 gigahertz that
 persist at detectable (submillijansky) levels for weeks,
