  Abstract                 = {Active galactic nuclei, which are powered by long-term
 accretion onto central supermassive black holes, produce
 relativistic jets with lifetimes of at least one million
 years, and the observation of the birth of such a jet is
 therefore unlikely. Transient accretion onto a supermassive
 black hole, for example through the tidal disruption of a
 stray star, thus offers a rare opportunity to study the
 birth of a relativistic jet. On 25 March 2011, an unusual
 transient source (Swift J164449.3+573451) was found,
